  "doc_id": "25506",
  "text": "In our case, the S. pyogenes was sensitive to penicillin G. Therefore, we used penicillin G and clindamycin as definitive therapies. We also used linezolid until the pathogen was identified because the possibility of community-acquired methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA) involvement could not be ruled out. The guidelines of the Infectious Disease Society of America recommend the use of penicillin plus clindamycin for the treatment of documented streptococcal necrotizing fasciitis [CITATION_1] . This recommendation is based on the finding that all strains of S. pyogenes are sensitive to penicillin and that clindamycin suppresses S. pyogenes exotoxin and M protein production. M protein is an important molecule for adhering to host cells; furthermore, it has anti-opsonin activity, which is associated with resistance to immunity. Moreover, the guidelines show that empirical treatment of polymicrobial necrotizing fasciitis should include agents that are effective against both aerobes, including MRSA, and anaerobes.",
  "correct_citation": {
